 > If we are using a reverse proxi, are the back and frontend changes still necessary?                                                
▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀
✦ Yes, most changes are still necessary, but the reverse proxy changes how you configure them. The reverse proxy handles the
  networking, but the application code still needs to know its identity.

  Here is why you still need to make those changes:

  1. Identity vs. Network Path
  The most important reason is the XMPP Domain. In XMPP, your "username" is actually a JID (like alice@your-domain.com). 
   * Prosody must be configured with VirtualHost "your-domain.com" so it knows to accept messages for that domain.
   * The Frontend must know your-domain.com to tell the browser which server to log into.
   * The Backend must know your-domain.com so it creates users with the correct ID in the database.

  Even if Nginx sits in front, if these three don't agree on the domain name, you won't be able to log in.

  2. What changes with a Reverse Proxy?

  If you use Nginx, your configuration becomes much cleaner. Instead of pointing to different ports, everything goes through the proxy port
  (8085).

  Frontend (.env)
  Instead of using IPs and ports, you use the public URLs:

   1 VITE_API_URL=https://chat.your-domain.com/api
   2 VITE_XMPP_DOMAIN=chat.your-domain.com

  Backend (main.py & .env)
  If you use Nginx to provide HTTPS, you must ensure the Backend knows its domain for CORS security.

   1 # In backend/main.py, you should eventually restrict this:
   2 app.add_middleware(
   3     CORSMiddleware,
   4     allow_origins=["https://chat.your-domain.com"], # Instead of ["*"]
   5     # ...
   6 )

  3. The "localhost" Problem in the Code
  As I mentioned earlier, there are several places in your current code where @localhost is hardcoded. A reverse proxy won't fix
  these; they will still produce user@localhost even if you are visiting https://my-cool-app.com.

  Example of what will break if you don't change the code:
   1. You register on my-cool-app.com.
   2. The Backend (hardcoded) creates a user bob@localhost.
   3. The Frontend (browser) tries to log in as bob@my-cool-app.com.
   4. Prosody rejects the login because bob@my-cool-app.com doesn't exist (only bob@localhost does).

  Summary: What to do
   1. Prosody: Update VirtualHost (This is mandatory).
   2. Frontend: Update VITE_XMPP_DOMAIN (This is mandatory).
   3. Backend: Replace hardcoded localhost strings with a variable (This is mandatory for the app to function).
   4. Nginx: Use it to handle SSL (HTTPS) and to map /api to the backend and /http-bind to Prosody. This makes the "regular browser"
      experience much better.



